\begin_layout Subsection
Regularization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The central idea that underlies regularization is simple: constrain the
 weights 
\begin_inset Formula $\bubeta$
\end_inset

 in some way so that they become more stable and/or more sparse, and computable
 even if 
\begin_inset Formula $p>N$
\end_inset

.
 For notational simplicity, we assume that all the columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{X}}$
\end_inset

 as well as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{y}}$
\end_inset

 are demeaned, so that the first element of 
\begin_inset Formula $\bubeta$
\end_inset

 corresponds to an explanatory variable, and not the intercept.
 This is standard practice when regularizing – it is variations from a baseline,
 not the baseline itself, that we are trying to fit, and shrinking the intercept
 will immediately introduce bias.
 Define
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left\Vert \bueps\right\Vert ^{2} & =\bueps^{\prime}\bueps.\nonumber \\
 & =\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{y}}\,-\,\mathrm{\mathbf{X}}\,\bubeta\right)^{\prime}\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{y}}\,-\,\mathrm{\mathbf{X}}\,\bubeta\right)\label{eq:SumEpsilonSquared}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\Vert \bubeta\right\Vert _{q}=\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{p}\left|\bubeta_{i}\right|^{q},\ \ q\geqslant0.\label{eq:qNormBeta}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While it is common practice to write
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \mathbf{x}\right\Vert _{q}=\left(\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{p}\left|\mathbf{x}_{i}\right|^{q}\right)^{1/q}$
\end_inset

, we have deliberately chosen not to raise the sum in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:qNormBeta"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 to the 
\begin_inset Formula $1/q^{th}$
\end_inset

 power as 
\begin_inset Formula $q=0$
\end_inset

 is an important special case – 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \bubeta\right\Vert _{0}$
\end_inset

 is just the number of non-zero components of 
\begin_inset Formula $\bubeta$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
It is standard practice in this context to assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $0^{0}=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 When 
\begin_inset Formula $q=1$
\end_inset

, it is the sum of their absolute values, and when 
\begin_inset Formula $q=2$
\end_inset

, it is the square of the Euclidean length of 
\begin_inset Formula $\bubeta$
\end_inset

.
 Regularization reformulates the least squares objective function to
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{\bubeta}_{q}=\underset{\bubeta}{\mathrm{argmin}}\ \left\Vert \bueps\right\Vert ^{2}\,+\,\lambda_{q}\left\Vert \bubeta\right\Vert _{q},\ \ q,\ \lambda_{q}\geqslant0\label{eq:RegularizationGeneral}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{q}=0$
\end_inset

, we are back to classical Least Squares for all 
\begin_inset Formula $q\geqslant0$
\end_inset

.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $q=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{0}>0$
\end_inset

, we are trading off Mean Squared Error against the number of predictor
 variables.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $q=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1}>0$
\end_inset

 , we are trading off Mean Squared Error against the sum of the magnitude
 of all the coefficients.
 This case is known as 
\emph on
lasso
\emph default
 (
\bar under
L
\bar default
east 
\bar under
A
\bar default
bsolute 
\bar under
S
\bar default
hrinkage and 
\bar under
S
\bar default
election 
\bar under
O
\bar default
perator, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Tibshirani1996"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Tibshirani2011"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $q=2$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{2}>0$
\end_inset

, we are trading off Mean Squared Error against the square of the Euclidean
 length of the coefficient vector.
 This case is known as 
\emph on
ridge regression
\emph default
 (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "HoerlKennard1970"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Hastie2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Technometrics devoted an entire issue (Vol 62, Issue 4, 2020) to celebrate
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $50^{th}$
\end_inset

 anniversary of ridge regression.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The optimal value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is determined using 
\emph on
cross-validation
\emph default
, which we discuss below.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:ContraintSurfaces"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 illustrates the shape of the constraint boundaries for lasso, ridge regression,
 and the elastic net, which is a weighted linear combination of the lasso
 and ridge penalties, with two explanatory variables.
 All three boundaries are convex, but only the latter two are strictly convex.
 The 
\family typewriter
R
\family default
 package 
\family typewriter
glmnet
\family default
 (
\begin_inset Flex URL
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

https://glmnet.stanford.edu/index.html
\end_layout

\end_inset

) provides efficient implementations of all these methods as well as many
 others.
 
\end_layout

