\begin_layout Subsection
Ridge Regression
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The objective function for ridge regression can be written in two equivalent
 ways:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Flex Subequations
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{\bubeta}_{ridge} & =\underset{\bubeta}{\mathrm{argmin}}\ \left\Vert \bueps\right\Vert ^{2}\,+\,\lambda\left\Vert \bubeta\right\Vert _{2},\ \ \lambda>0\label{eq:RidgeRegressionA}\\
 & =\underset{\bubeta}{\mathrm{argmin}}\ \left\Vert \bueps\right\Vert ^{2},\ \ \mathrm{s.t.}\left\Vert \bubeta\right\Vert _{2}\leqslant c,\ c>0\label{eq:RidgeRegressionB}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These formulations echo the two ways in which efficient frontiers can be
 computed (the Lagrangian formulation and the bound formulation), but the
 Lagrangian formulation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:RidgeRegressionA"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is easier to deal with analytically.
 The bound formulation makes clear that 
\begin_inset Formula $\bubeta$
\end_inset

 lies on or inside the surface of a hypersphere of radius 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{c}.$
\end_inset

 In fact, it mirrors the formulation of mean-variance efficient portfolio
 construction covered in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
FoundationsChapter
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ridge regression was originally proposed by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "HoerlKennard1970"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 as an ad-hoc solution to the problem of collinearity in least squares.
 It is sometimes said to get its name from the fact that it adds a stabilizing
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

raised ridge
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to the diagonal of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{X}}^{\prime}\ \mathrm{\mathbf{X}}$
\end_inset

.
 The quadratic penalty term ensures that closed form solutions to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:RidgeRegressionA"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:RidgeRegressionB"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 always exists, and it is left as an exercise to show that 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{\bubeta}_{ridge}=\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{X}}_{p\times N}^{\prime}\,\mathrm{\mathbf{X}}_{N\times p}\,+\,\lambda\,\mathbf{I}_{p\times p}\right)^{-1}\,\mathrm{\mathbf{X}}_{p\times N}^{\prime}\,\mathrm{\mathbf{y}}_{N\times1},\label{eq:RidgeRegressionSolution}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
that the 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{X}}_{p\times N}^{\prime}\,\mathrm{\mathbf{X}}_{N\times p}\,+\,\lambda\,\mathbf{I}_{p\times p}$
\end_inset

 can be obtained by adding 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 to the eigenvalues of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{X}}_{p\times N}^{\prime}\,\mathrm{\mathbf{X}}_{N\times p}$
\end_inset

, and that the eigenvectors of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{X}}_{p\times N}^{\prime}\,\mathrm{\mathbf{X}}_{N\times p}\,+\,\lambda\,\mathbf{I}_{p\times p}$
\end_inset

 are identical to the eigenvectors of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{X}}_{p\times N}^{\prime}\,\mathrm{\mathbf{X}}_{N\times p}$
\end_inset

.
 Simple rearrangement of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:OLS2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:RidgeRegressionSolution"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 shows that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{\bubeta}_{ridge}=\left(\mathbf{I}_{p\times p}\,+\,\lambda\,\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{X}}_{p\times N}^{\prime}\,\mathrm{\mathbf{X}}_{N\times p}\right)^{-1}\right)^{-1}\hat{\bubeta}_{LS}.\label{eq:RidgevsLSbeta}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the special case when the columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{X}$
\end_inset

 are orthonormal (i.e.
 are orthogonal and and have unit variance), 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:RidgevsLSbeta"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 reduces to
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{\bubeta}_{ridge}=\frac{\hat{\bubeta}_{LS}}{1+\lambda}.\label{eq:RidgevsLSbetaOrthogonal}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Ridge regression is not linearly equivariant – the bracketed term in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:RidgeRegressionSolution"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 makes clear that the regularization penalty, being additive, is proportionately
 larger for columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{X}$
\end_inset

 with low variance.
 It is the norm, therefore, to pre-process 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{X}$
\end_inset

 ahead of solving 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:RidgeRegressionSolution"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 by standardizing all its columns so that they have a sample mean of 0 and
 a sample variance of 1.
 Also, ridge regression does not reduce the number of coefficients in a
 model – it simply shrinks them all towards zero and each other as 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 increases.
 The optimal value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 must be determined using cross-validation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Hastie2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 uses the Singular Value Decomposition (SVD) to show that if two or more
 of columns in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{X}}$
\end_inset

 are identical, ridge regression will assign each one of them identical
 coefficients that sum to the same value that would be assigned to the single
 column that remains after all the duplicates are excised.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Theobald1974"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 proves that the covariance matrix of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\bubeta}_{ridge}$
\end_inset

 is smaller than that of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\bubeta}_{LS}$
\end_inset

 for some value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda>0.$
\end_inset

 It follows that the ridge estimator is necessarily biased, as the Gauss-Markov
 Theorem (see 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
ProbabilityAppendix
\end_layout

\end_inset

) assures us that least squares is the best linear unbiased estimator of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{y}}$
\end_inset

 and minimizes the covariance matrix of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\bubeta}_{LS}$
\end_inset

.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is small, ridge regression is almost identical to least squares, and its
 estimates are essentially unbiased.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 increases, the coefficients are shrunk to 0: their variance declines, but
 their bias increases.
 At the optimal value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

, the MSE, which is the sum of the variance and the square of the bias,
 is minimized.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is a deep link between ridge regression and the Singular Value Decompositi
on.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
See 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
MathToolsAppendix
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

for a discussion of the SVD.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If we write
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{\mathbf{X}}_{N\times p}=\mathrm{\mathbf{U}}_{N\times N}\mathrm{\mathbf{D}}_{N\times p}\mathrm{\mathbf{V}}_{p\times p}^{\prime},\label{eq:SVDofX}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
with 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathrm{\mathbf{U}}^{\prime}\,\mathrm{\mathbf{U}}\,=\,\mathrm{\mathbf{V}}^{\prime}\,\mathrm{\mathbf{V}}\,=\,\mathrm{\mathbf{I}},\label{eq:UandVareOrthogonal}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{D}}_{N\times p}$
\end_inset

 diagonal in the sense that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{D}}_{11}\,\geqslant\,\mathrm{\mathbf{D}}_{22}\,\geqslant\mathrm{\mathbf{D}}_{22}\geqslant\mathrm{\mathbf{D}}_{\min(N,\ p),\ \min(N,\ p)}\geqslant0$
\end_inset

, and substitute 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SVDofX"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:RidgeRegressionSolution"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and simplify, we get
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{\bubeta}_{ridge}=\sum_{i\ s.t.\ \mathbf{D}_{i\,i}>0}\mathbf{v}_{i}\frac{\mathbf{D}_{i\,i}}{\mathbf{D}_{i\,i}^{2}+\lambda}\,\mathbf{u}_{i}\cdot\mathbf{y}\label{eq:RidgeBetaViaSVD}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{i}$
\end_inset

 are the left and right singular vectors of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{X}$
\end_inset

.
 The fitted values are easily seen to be
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{\mathrm{\mathbf{y}}} & =\mathbf{X}\,\hat{\bubeta}_{ridge}\nonumber \\
 & =\mathrm{\mathbf{U}}\,\mathrm{\mathbf{D}}\,\mathrm{\mathbf{V}}^{\prime}\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{D}}^{\prime}\,\mathrm{\mathbf{D}}\ +\ \lambda\,\mathbf{I}\right)^{-1}\mathrm{\mathbf{V}}\,\mathrm{\mathbf{D}}\,\mathrm{\mathbf{U}^{\prime}}\,\mathbf{y}\nonumber \\
 & =\sum_{i\ s.t.\ \mathbf{D}_{i\,i}\,>\,0}\mathbf{u}_{i}\,\frac{\mathbf{D}_{i\,i}^{2}}{\mathbf{D}_{i\,i}^{2}+\lambda}\,\mathbf{u}_{i}\cdot\mathbf{y}.\label{eq:RidgeYhatViaSVD}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Once the SVD of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{X}$
\end_inset

 has been identified and the inner products 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}_{i}\cdot\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 computed, the entire ridge solution is known.
 The SVD representation of ridge regression makes clear that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Small singular values are shrunk more than large singular values, and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The large singular values do not necessarily contribute to the prediction
 – the dot product of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

is just as important as the magnitude of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{D}_{i\,i}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second observation has an important practical implication: care must
 be taken when discarding terms in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:RidgeBetaViaSVD"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:RidgeYhatViaSVD"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 The common practice of discarding small eigenvalues (in Principal Components
 Regression) or singular values (in SVD) can result in the inadvertent deletion
 of precisely those components of the data in which its explanatory power
 is most highly concentrated.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Projection Pursuit Analysis (PPA) and Independent Components Analyis (ICA)
 provide useful alternatives to PCA and SVD in such situations, as they
 identify directions along which the separation between classes is maximized.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda\longrightarrow0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:RidgeBetaViaSVD"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:RidgeYhatViaSVD"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 converge to the OLS solution 
\emph on
even when the system of equations is under determined
\emph default
 (i.e.
 when 
\begin_inset Formula $p>N)$
\end_inset

.
 In this case 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:RidgeBetaViaSVD"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:RidgeYhatViaSVD"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 represent the OLS solution that minimizes 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \bubeta\right\Vert _{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In spite of its simplicity and its inability to select a subset of the explanato
ry variables, ridge regression has proved to be a powerful way in which
 to balance bias and variance while minimizing MSE, and it plays a fundamental
 role in data science and machine learning.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Hastie2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "vanWieringen2023"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 usefully collect five decades of insights into its many benefits, as well
 as its relationship to other concepts in Bayesian statistics and data science.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Lasso 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Lasso 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Lasso is an acronym for 
\bar under
L
\bar default
east 
\bar under
A
\bar default
bsolute 
\bar under
S
\bar default
hrinkage and 
\bar under
S
\bar default
election 
\bar under
O
\bar default
perator.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 replaces ridge regression's quadratic penalty with a linear (in absolute
 value) penalty.
 As in the case of ridge regression, the objective function for lasso can
 be written using either a Lagrangian or a bound formulation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Flex Subequations
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{\bubeta}_{lasso} & =\underset{\bubeta}{\mathrm{argmin}}\ \left\Vert \bueps\right\Vert ^{2}\,+\,\lambda\left\Vert \bubeta\right\Vert _{1},\ \ \lambda>0\label{eq:LassoA}\\
 & =\underset{\bubeta}{\mathrm{argmin}}\ \left\Vert \bueps\right\Vert ^{2},\ \ \mathrm{s.t.}\left\Vert \bubeta\right\Vert _{1}<c,\ c>0\label{eq:LassoB}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the special case when the columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{X}$
\end_inset

 are orthonormal, it can be shown that the solution to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:LassoA"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{\bubeta}_{lasso}=\left(\left|\hat{\bubeta}_{LS}\right|\,-\,\frac{\lambda}{2}\boldsymbol{1}\right)^{+}\odot\mathrm{sgn}\left(\hat{\bubeta}_{LS}\right),\label{eq:LassovsLSbeta}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{1}$
\end_inset

 is a column vector of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 1's, 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{+}=\max\left(x,\,0\right)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\odot$
\end_inset

 denotes the element-wise (or Hadamard) product of the two vectors, and
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{sgn}\left(x\right)=1\ \forall\ x\geqslant0$
\end_inset

 and -1 otherwise.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Turning to 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
ConstraintsAndPenaltiesChapter
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

for insight, we see that the computation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\bubeta}_{lasso}$
\end_inset

 is a constrained quadratic program that can be solved using the computationally
 efficient LARS (Least Angle Regression) algorithm first described in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "EfronHastieJohnstoneTibshirani2004"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "TibshiraniRyan2013"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 proves that the solution to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:LassoA"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:LassoB"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is unique with probability 1 if the entries of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{X}$
\end_inset

 are drawn from a continuous distribution, and also describes an enhanced
 LARS algorithm that is implemented in the 
\family typewriter
R
\family default
 package 
\family typewriter
glmnet
\family default
, which implements a wide range of linear models.
 Even when the entries of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{X}$
\end_inset

 are not drawn from a continuous distribution, and if two or more solutions
 exist, they are equivalent in that they have the same optimal value and
 level of sparsity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The optimal value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 must be chosen using cross-validation.
 The bound formulation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:LassoB"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 makes clear that 
\begin_inset Formula $\bubeta$
\end_inset

 lies on a surface defined by intersecting planes.
 The sharp corners at the intersections of these planes make the objective
 function not differentiable at these points and induce a sparsity property
 – unlike ridge regression, lasso naturally selects a subset of the explanatory
 variables and assigns zero weight to the others.
 Its great disadvantage (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Breiman1996a"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) is that it can be unstable – both 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \bueps\right\Vert ^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\bubeta}_{lasso}$
\end_inset

 can change dramatically when small changes are made to the selected subset
 of explanatory variables, or when new cases are added to the data.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Put differently, lasso lacks the 
\emph on
oracle property
\emph default
: if the true model is based on a subset 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

 of the available regressors with cardinality 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{\prime}<p$
\end_inset

, then as 
\begin_inset Formula $N\longrightarrow\infty$
\end_inset

, an oracular algorithm will exhibit the following features: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Flex Subequations
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{\bubeta}_{i},\ i\notin\mathcal{P} & =0\label{eq:OracleLassoA}\\
\sqrt{N}\left(\hat{\bubeta}_{\mathcal{P}}-\bubeta_{\mathcal{P}}\right) & \longrightarrow N\left(\mathbf{0},\ \buSigma^{*}\right),\label{eq:OracleLassoB}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\buSigma^{*}$
\end_inset

 is the covariance matrix of the true subset model.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The details are technical; we refer the reader to 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "FanLi2001"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Zou2006"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for a careful exploration of the oracle property as well as the relevant
 proofs.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Zou2006"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 shows that the 
\emph on
adaptive lasso
\emph default
 achieves the oracle property if the terms in the lasso's penalty function
 are suitably weighted, i.e.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{\bubeta}_{adaptive\ lasso}=\underset{\bubeta}{\mathrm{argmin}}\ \left\Vert \bueps\right\Vert ^{2}\,+\,\lambda\sum_{i=1}^{p}w_{i}\left|\bubeta\right|_{i},\ \ \lambda>0\label{eq:AdaptiveLasso}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where the weights 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{i}$
\end_inset

 are derived from the coefficients of some other 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{N}-$
\end_inset

consistent estimator of 
\begin_inset Formula $\bubeta$
\end_inset

 such as ridge regression.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Zou2006"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 uses both LS and ridge weights, and defines
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
w_{i}=\left(\frac{1}{\left|\bubeta_{\sqrt{N}-consistent,\ i}\right|}\right)^{\gamma},\ \gamma>0.\label{eq:AdaptiveLassoWeights}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In essence, when the coefficients of the ancillary estimator are small,
 the penalty in the lasso is amplified, so that the entries of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\bubeta}_{adaptive\ lasso}$
\end_inset

 corresponding to noise are more likely to be set to 0.
 Both 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 must be determined empirically using cross-validation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Lasso is far more efficient computationally than the natural way in which
 to maximize sparsity, which is to identify the best subset of the explanatory
 variables.
 The best subset approach creates all 
\begin_inset Formula $2^{m}-1$
\end_inset

 possible subsets of the 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 explanatory variables, regresses 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 against each one of these subsets, and finally selects the subset with
 smallest forecast error.
 The complexity of best subset selection grows rapidly with both 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

, though 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "BertsimasKingMazumder2016"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 describe an efficient mixed integer programming algorithm that solves the
 best subset problem for 
\begin_inset Formula $m\approx100$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N\approx1000$
\end_inset

 in a few minutes.
 The primary advantage of the best subset selection approach is that it
 cleanly eliminates noise variables that might display some spurious correlation
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "HastieTibshiraniTibshirani2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 compare lasso to best subset as well as a variant of lasso known as 
\emph on
relaxed lasso
\emph default
 in which lasso is first used to identify the relevant variables, and least
 squares is then used to determine their coefficients.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Formally, let 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

 be the set of variables chosen by lasso for a given value of lambda, and
 let 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\bubeta}_{LS}\left(S_{\lambda}\right)$
\end_inset

 be the least squares coefficient vector when 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 is regressed against the subset of columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{X}$
\end_inset

 corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{\lambda}$
\end_inset

.
 To ensure that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\bubeta}_{LS}\left(S_{\lambda}\right)$
\end_inset

 has length 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, we pad it with zeroes in positions corresponding to variables that are
 not selected.
 The relaxed lasso estimator is a weighted average of the pure lasso estimate
 and the restricted least squares estimate, i.e.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{\bubeta}_{relaxed\ lasso}\left(\lambda,\ \gamma\right)=\gamma\,\hat{\bubeta}_{lasso}\,+\,(1-\gamma)\hat{\bubeta}_{LS}\left(S_{\lambda}\right),\ 0<\lambda,\ 0\leqslant\gamma\leqslant1.\label{eq:RelaxedLasso}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The optimal values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 must be determined from cross-validation, and an upper bound on 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 can be obtained by testing a few cases till one is found that forces all
 (or almost all) the coefficients to 0.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Lasso, unlike ridge regression, tends to perform poorly when two or more
 of the variables are highly correlated.
 The total weight assigned to the highly correlated group can be distributed
 in very different proportions among the correlated variates with little
 impact on the objective function.
 Ridge regression, on the other hand, will tend to weight them equally as
 its quadratic penalty diminishes when there is an even allocation between
 highly correlated variables.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This observation is of practical importance: it sometimes proves necessary
 to include or exclude a complete (predefined) set of columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{X}$
\end_inset

, as, for example, when a categorical variable is encoded by a set of 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 dummy variables, the 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{th}$
\end_inset

 one of which is 1 (all the other 
\begin_inset Formula $l-1$
\end_inset

 are 0) according to whether or the particular observation is associated
 with category 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 The grouping problem arises naturally in machine learning, and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "YuanLin2006"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 solve it using a variant of lasso they call group lasso.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "HastieTibshiraniTibshirani2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 conduct a series of experiments comparing lasso and relaxed lasso to best
 subset selection and forward stepwise selection.When the signal-to-noise
 ratio (SNR) is low, lasso tends to perform better than best subset selection
 and forward stepwise selection.
 When it is high, the reverse is true.
 Relaxed lasso turns out to be the overall winner – it performs about as
 well as lasso when SNR is low, and about as well as best subset selection
 when it is high.
 While no single method uniformly dominates the others, it is important
 to keep in mind that it is the low SNR case that is of greatest relevance
 to finance, making lasso and relaxed lasso useful starting points for machine
 learning in finance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Elastic Net 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "ZouHastie2005"
literal "false"

\end_inset

