\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 is the sample correlation between the 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{th}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j^{th}$
\end_inset

columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{X}$
\end_inset

 (see Theorem 1 and Appendix A of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "ZouHastie2005"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for a proof).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In practice, though, the na
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash

\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

{i}
\end_layout

\end_inset

ve elastic net tends to shrink too much – its solution is first impacted
 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{2}$
\end_inset

 (which induces shrinkage as does ridge regression when the columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{X}$
\end_inset

 are orthogonal – see 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:RidgevsLSbetaOrthogonal"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) and then by 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1}$
\end_inset

, which induces further lasso-like selection.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "ZouHastie2005"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 suggest a pragmatic solution to this problem – they undo the ridge-like
 shrinkage by scaling the coefficients of the na
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash

\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

{i}
\end_layout

\end_inset

ve elastic net by 
\begin_inset Formula $1\,+\,\lambda_{2}$
\end_inset

 and transform the na
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash

\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

{i}
\end_layout

\end_inset

ve elastic net into the 
\emph on
elastic net
\emph default
:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{\bubeta}_{elastic\ net} & =\left(1\,+\,\lambda_{2}\right)\times\hat{\bubeta}_{na\ddot{i}ve\ elastic\ net}\nonumber \\
 & =\sqrt{1\,+\,\lambda_{2}}\times\left[\underset{\bubeta^{*}}{\mathrm{argmin}}\left\Vert \bueps^{*}\right\Vert ^{2}\,+\,\gamma\,\left\Vert \bubeta^{*}\right\Vert _{1}\right],\ \ \gamma>0.\label{eq:BetaElasticNet}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By doing so, they preserve the variable selection property of lasso and
 induce the desirable variable grouping property we earlier described.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "ZouZhang2009"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 show that a variant of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:BetaElasticNet"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 that they call the 
\emph on
adaptive elastic net
\emph default
 exhibits the oracle property.
 As in the case of the adaptive lasso, they first identify 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\bubeta}_{elastic\ net}$
\end_inset

, and then use these coefficients to weight the individual components of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \bubeta^{*}\right\Vert _{1}$
\end_inset

 in a second model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{\bubeta}_{adaptive\ elastic\ net}=\left(1\,+\,\lambda_{2}\right)\times\underset{\bubeta}{\mathrm{argmin}}\left\Vert \bueps\right\Vert ^{2}\,+\,\lambda_{1}\sum_{i=1}^{p}w_{i}\left|\bubeta\right|_{i}\,+\,\lambda_{2}\left\Vert \bubeta\right\Vert _{2},\ \ \lambda_{1},\ \lambda_{2}>0\label{eq:AdaptiveElasticNet}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
w_{i}=\left(\frac{1}{\left|\bubeta_{elastic\ net,\ i}\right|}\right)^{\gamma},\ \gamma>0.\label{eq:AdaptiveElasticNetWeights}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As in the case of the adaptive lasso, small elastic net coefficients amplify
 the corresponding terms penalty in the adaptive elastic net, making the
 removal of noise coefficients more likely.
 Both 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 must be determined empirically using cross-validation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Cross-Validation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Cross-validation involves splitting the training data set into two or more
 parts, some of which are used for model building, and others that are used
 for model testing ahead of implementation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Leave-out-one cross-validation is the simplest form of cross-validation,
 and is applicable to data without a temporal component (i.e.
 without a well defined notion of past, present and future).
 From a data set with 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 items, we create 
\begin_inset Formula $N-1$
\end_inset

 data sets with 
\begin_inset Formula $N-1$
\end_inset

 items each by removing the 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{th}$
\end_inset

 row of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{X}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{y}}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $1\leqslant i\leqslant N$
\end_inset

.
 Next, we build 
\begin_inset Formula $N-1$
\end_inset

 models using our preferred modeling technique, and use these to forecast
 the excluded observations 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{y}}_{i}$
\end_inset

 one at a time.
 The mean squared error is a function of both the modeling technique and
 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 and is given by
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
MSE\left(\lambda\right)=\frac{1}{N}\sum_{i=1}^{N}\left(\hat{\mathrm{\mathbf{y}}_{i}}-\mathrm{\mathbf{y}}_{i}\ |\ \lambda\right)^{2}\label{eq:MSECrossValidation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mathrm{\mathbf{y}}_{i}}$
\end_inset

 is the forecast of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{y}}_{i}$
\end_inset

 made using the model built on the remaining 
\begin_inset Formula $N-1$
\end_inset

 rows of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{X}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\mathbf{y}}$
\end_inset

.
 The value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 must be determined by minimizing 
\begin_inset Formula $MSE$
\end_inset

 over all possible values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\lambda^{*}=\underset{\lambda}{\mathrm{argmin}\ }MSE\left(\lambda\right).\label{eq:OptimalLambda}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An upper bound on 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 can be obtained by testing a few cases till one is found that forces all
 (or almost all) the coefficients to 0, and the cross-validation procedure
 can then examine a grid of values between 0 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{max}$
\end_inset

.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is so large that leave-out-one cross-validation is computationally prohibitive,
 cross-validation can also be done with a 
\begin_inset Formula $k-$
\end_inset

fold split: the data is broken up into 
\begin_inset Formula $k<<N$
\end_inset

 subgroups of approximately equal size; 
\begin_inset Formula $k-1$
\end_inset

 of which are used as a training set, with the last one being used as a
 validation set.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "BreimanSpector1992"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 suggest that 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 be set to 5, though 10 is also commonly used.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When the data has a temporal component, a 
\emph on
training-validation-testing
\emph default
 data split is common: the data is split into three parts.
 The oldest part (the training set) is used to build models with a wide
 range of values for 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 The middle part (the validation set), is used to test each model built
 using the training set.
 Finally, the model (or the parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

) that gives rise to the best forecasts in the validation set is identified,
 and is then applied to the most recent part (the testing set).
 It is important that the testing data set be held out and completely unavailabl
e to the algorithm during training and validation, as viewing it ahead of
 time is equivalent to looking into the future.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Parameter identification for temporal data can be done in other ways as
 well.
 For example, we use expanding window robust regressions in 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
ExpectedReturnChapter
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

to forecast the forward returns of the S&P 500 Index.
 Assume we have data for time periods 
\begin_inset Formula $1,\ 2,\ \cdots,\ T$
\end_inset

.
 We start by fitting a model using robust regression over some initial time
 period 
\begin_inset Formula $1,\ 2,\ \cdots,\ T_{0}$
\end_inset

, and then test its prediction for time period 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{0}+1$
\end_inset

.
 We then build a new model using data over an expanded window 
\begin_inset Formula $1,\ 2,\ \cdots,\ T_{0}+1$
\end_inset

 and test its prediction for time period 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{0}+2$
\end_inset

.
 Each period the training window expands by one to allow the incorporation
 of new data, and this process is continued till the data is exhausted.
 The entire loop can be repeated using different values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 before choosing a final value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 for use with the next incoming observation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
I have never been convinced of expanding window regression, primarily because
 it is not time adaptive enough.
 INTERESTINGLY, IT IS CENTRAL TO PORTFOLIO MANAGEMENT, BECAUSE REGIMES CHANGE,
 AND YOU DON'T WANT TO JUST FIT YOUR MODEL ON THE MOST RECENT REGIME - YOU
 ARE BETTER OFF FITTING OVER A WIDE RANGE OF REGIMES.
 I USE IT FOR THE S&P 500 RETURN PREDICTION PROBLEM IN THE EXPECTED RETURN
 CHAPTER.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Robust Regularized Regression
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Even though robust statistical methods have made inroads into statistical
 modeling and have seen some application in portfolio management as in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "MartinStoyanovLiShammaa2023"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "MartinGuerardXia2024"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
and portfolio management, 
\series bold
This is most definitely not the case, and we can cite our 2023 JPM paper
 as kind of a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

first
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 on the topic.
 DONE
\end_layout

\end_inset

 they are far from being a standard method in the field of machine learning.
 A notable exception is the use of a well-known Huber method of controlling
 for outliers in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "GuKellyXiu2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Even so, some robust analogues of the methods described in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:ClassicalSupervisedLearning"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 exist, and we expect many more to be developed in the near future.
 The R package 
\family typewriter
pense
\family default
 has robust extensions of ridge, lasso and elastic net estimators, and a
 good discussion of these methods can be found in Chapter 5 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Maronna2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 as well as in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "FreueKepplingerSalibianSmucler2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 We use it for all our work.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The central idea in robust regularization is to replace 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \bueps\right\Vert ^{2}$
\end_inset

 in the various objective functions with 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i}\rho\left(\nicefrac{\bueps_{i}\,}{\,\hat{s}}\right)$
\end_inset

 for some symmetric loss function 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(.)$
\end_inset

 and some robust estimator of scale 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{s}$
\end_inset

 .
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
It is a current limitation of most work in this area, as well as of 
\family typewriter
pense
\family default
, that they use Tukey's Bisquare for their 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 function.
 While Tukey's bisquare does have some desirable properties (it is bounded,
 and its corresponding 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 function is redescending), the mOpt 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 function is better, and we expect that the authors of 
\family typewriter
pense
\family default
 will eventually replace Tukey's Bisquare with mOpt.
 
\series bold
This is not really the case.
 The most important thing is that the rho function must be 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

reasonably
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 bounded, and the main argument in favor of mOpt over the Bisquare is that
 mOpt is supported by a theoretical result, whereas the Bisquare is not,
 and the mOpt shape is more intuitive as a robust 3-sigma edit rule.
 For the latter, see Figure 6.2 of Chapter 6, and the text immediately following,
 and for the former see Section 18.4.4 of Chapter 18.
 AGREED
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Robust Ridge Regression
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Maronna2011"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 describes a robust algorithm for ridge regression that is best thought
 of as a weighted version of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:RidgeRegressionA"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 with data dependent weights 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{w}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{w}_{i},\ 1\leqslant i\leqslant N$
\end_inset

 is the weight applied to the 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{th}$
\end_inset

 row of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{X}$
\end_inset

.
 If we let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{W}_{N\times N}=diag(\mathbf{w})$
\end_inset

, the robust equivalent of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:RidgeRegressionA"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{\mu},\ \hat{\bubeta}_{robust\ ridge}=\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{X}}_{p\times N}^{\prime}\,\mathbf{W}_{N\times N}\,\mathrm{\mathbf{X}}_{N\times p}\,+\,\lambda\,\mathbf{I}_{p\times p}\right)^{-1}\,\mathrm{\mathbf{X}}_{p\times N}^{\prime}\,\mathbf{W}_{N\times N}\,\left(\mathrm{\mathbf{y}}_{N\times1}-\hat{\mu}\boldsymbol{1}_{N\times1}\right),\label{eq:RobustRidgeRegressionSolution}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mu},\ \hat{\bubeta}_{robust\ ridge}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{W}_{N\times N}$
\end_inset

 must be identified iteratively.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Earlier, we could safely assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

 was demeaned so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mu}$
\end_inset

 could be set to 0, but in the presence of outliers, this is no longer true,
 and the algorithm must provide a robust estimate of its location.
 The weights 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{w}_{i}=\frac{\psi(\bueps_{i})}{\bueps_{i}}\label{eq:RobustRidgeWeights}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
are determined by applying 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
RobustWeightsDefinition
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

 to the residuals 
\begin_inset Formula $\bueps$
\end_inset

 obtained from
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\bueps=\mathbf{y}\,-\hat{\mu}\,\boldsymbol{1}_{N}\,\mathbf{-\,X}\ \hat{\bubeta}_{robust\ ridge}.\label{eq:RobustRidgeResiduals}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Maronna2011"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 starts by using a highly robust (but potentially inefficient) regression
 estimator to obtain an initial estimate of the regression coefficients
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mu}_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\bubeta}_{0}$
\end_inset

, following which the residuals 
\begin_inset Formula $\bueps_{0}$
\end_inset

 are computed.
 He then obtains an initial estimate of their scale, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\sigma}_{0}$
\end_inset

, by solving
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{1}{N}\sum_{i\thinspace=\,1}^{N}\rho_{0}\left(\frac{\bueps_{0,\ i}}{\hat{\sigma}_{0}}\right)=\delta,\label{eq:IntializeSigmaEstimate}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\rho_{0}(x)=\rho_{Bisquare}\left(\frac{x}{c_{0}}\right)=\min\left(1,\ 1\,-\,\left(1-\left(\frac{x}{c_{0}}\right)^{2}\right)^{3}\right),\label{eq:ScaledBisquareRhoc}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{0}$
\end_inset

 determine the algorithm's robustness.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next, using the initial estimate of scale, as well as an estimate of the
 equivalent degrees of freedom in the data, the algorithm adjusts 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{0}$
\end_inset

 upwards to a new value 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 that assures a desired level of normal efficiency when minimizing the loss
 function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathscr{L}\left(\mathbf{X},\ \mathbf{y},\ \mu,\ \bubeta\right)=\hat{\sigma}_{0}^{2}\cdot\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{N}\rho\left(\frac{\mu,\ \bueps_{i}\left(\bubeta\right)}{\hat{\sigma}_{0}}\right)+\lambda\left\Vert \bubeta\right\Vert _{2},\label{eq:RobustRidgeLoss}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\rho(x)=\rho_{Bisquare}\left(\frac{x}{c}\right)=\min\left(1,\ 1\,-\,\left(1-\left(\frac{x}{c}\right)^{2}\right)^{3}\right).\label{eq:ScaledBisquareRho}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, using weights derived from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:RobustRidgeWeights"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:RobustRidgeLoss"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ScaledBisquareRho"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, the iterative procedure repeatedly updates 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{W},\ \hat{\bubeta}_{robust\ ridge},$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\mu}$
\end_inset

 till the changes in 
\begin_inset Formula $\bueps$
\end_inset

 are sufficiently small.
 The algorithm has a number of subtleties, starting with the fact that its
 robustness depends on both the initial estimate of scale and the effective
 number of parameters, and these are covered in Section 5.10 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Maronna2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We recommend implementing robust ridge regression using the function 
\family typewriter
regmest
\family default
 in the R package 
\family typewriter
pense
\family default
 with the parameter 
\family typewriter
alpha
\family default
 set to 0.
 If a cross validated robust ridge regression is required, the corresponding
 function is 
\family typewriter
regmest_cv()
\family default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Robust Lasso and Elastic Net
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "FreueKepplingerSalibianSmucler2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 describe a flexible family of robust estimators that can implement models
 ranging from ridge regression through elastic net to lasso by changing
 a single parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 in the loss functions.
 They consider two loss functions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Flex Subequations
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathscr{L}_{PS}\left(\mathbf{X},\ \mathbf{y},\ \mu,\ \bubeta\right) & =\sigma^{2}\left(\mu,\ \bubeta\right)\,+\,\lambda_{S}\left(\alpha\left\Vert \bubeta\right\Vert _{1}\,+\,\frac{\left(1-\alpha\right)}{2}\left\Vert \bubeta\right\Vert _{2}\right),\ \ \lambda_{S}>0,\ 0\leqslant\alpha\leqslant1\label{eq:SestimatorLoss}\\
\mathscr{L}_{PM}\left(\mathbf{X},\ \mathbf{y},\ \mu,\ \bubeta\right) & =\frac{1}{N}\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{N}\rho\left(\frac{\bueps_{i}\left(\mu,\ \bubeta\right)}{\hat{\sigma}_{0}}\right)\,+\,\lambda_{M}\left(\alpha\left\Vert \bubeta\right\Vert _{1}\,+\,\frac{\left(1-\alpha\right)}{2}\left\Vert \bubeta\right\Vert _{2}\right),\ \ \lambda_{M}>0,\ 0\leqslant\alpha\leqslant1.\label{eq:MestimatorLoss}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The presence of the variance in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:SestimatorLoss"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 identifies it as the loss function of an S-estimator (S stands for scale)
 and the presence of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 function in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:MestimatorLoss"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 identifies it as an M-estimator.
 The corresponding estimators are known as PENSE (
\bar under
P
\bar default
enalized 
\bar under
E
\bar default
lastic 
\bar under
N
\bar default
et 
\bar under
S
\bar default
 
\bar under
E
\bar default
stimator) and PENSEM (
\bar under
P
\bar default
enalized 
\bar under
E
\bar default
lastic 
\bar under
N
\bar default
et 
\bar under
S
\bar default
 
\bar under
E
\bar default
stimator – 
\bar under
M
\bar default
 step).
 The factor of 2 in the regularization penalty and 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{N}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:MestimatorLoss"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 are not essential - we follow the convention adopted by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "FreueKepplingerSalibianSmucler2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 to allow easy cross-referencing.
 These scaling factors do not affect the solutions to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:SestimatorLoss"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:MestimatorLoss"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, but make them easier to manipulate algebraically and interpret.
 The factor of 2 cancels when 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \bubeta\right\Vert _{2}$
\end_inset

 is differentiated, and the factor of 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{N}$
\end_inset

 permits us to interpret the first term of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:MestimatorLoss"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 as an expectation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Kepplinger2023"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "KepplingerCohen2023"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 describe adaptive versions of PENSE and PENSEM that reduce the bias of
 large coefficients and improves their ability to select variables.
 An initial estimate of 
\begin_inset Formula $\bubeta$
\end_inset

 is obtained using robust ridge regression, and these coefficients are then
 used to weight both the magnitude and the square of the individual components
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\bubeta$
\end_inset

.
 The revised loss functions are
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Flex Subequations
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathscr{L}_{APS}\left(\mathbf{X},\ \mathbf{y},\ \mu,\ \bubeta\right) & =\sigma^{2}\left(\mu,\ \bubeta\right)\,+\,\lambda_{S}\,\sum_{i=1}^{p}w_{i}\left(\alpha\,\left|\bubeta_{i}\right|\,+\,\frac{1-\alpha}{2}\bubeta_{i}^{2}\right),\ \ \lambda_{S}>0,\ 0\leqslant\alpha\leqslant1\label{eq:AdaptiveSestimatorLoss}\\
\mathscr{L}_{APM}\left(\mathbf{X},\ \mathbf{y},\ \mu,\ \bubeta\right) & =\frac{1}{N}\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{N}\rho\left(\frac{\bueps_{i}\left(\mu,\ \bubeta\right)}{\hat{\sigma}_{0}}\right)\,+\,\lambda_{M}\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{p}w_{i}\left(\alpha\,\left|\bubeta_{i}\right|\,+\,\frac{1-\alpha}{2}\bubeta_{i}^{2}\right),\ \ \lambda_{M}>0,\ 0\leqslant\alpha\leqslant1.\label{eq:AdaptiveMestimatorLoss}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
w_{i}=\left(\frac{1}{\left|\bubeta_{robust\ ridge,\ i}\right|}\right)^{\gamma},\ \gamma>0.\label{eq:AdaptiveElasticNetWeights-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The function 
\family typewriter
adamest_cv(
\family default
) in 
\family typewriter
pense
\family default
 implements adaptive scaling for both lasso and elastic net.
 As with all regularized models, the loss function must be minimized using
 cross-validation, though, as the data might contain outliers, 
\begin_inset Formula $MSE$
\end_inset

 is no longer a good measure of the prediction error, which must be measured
 using a robust estimator of scale.
 The cross-validation functions in 
\family typewriter
pense
\family default
 allow the user to specify a range of classical and robust measures of predictio
n error.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We have something unique to offer here.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We need rich, convincing applications examples, which compare Classic (LS
 based) and Robust Regularized Regression
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Classification and Robust Logistic regression 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sometimes, we are tasked with mapping a set of features to a set of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 distinct classes, or categories, of responses 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{1},\,C_{2},\cdots,\,C_{K}$
\end_inset

, such as the digits 0–9 (
\begin_inset Formula $K=10$
\end_inset

), or the recessionary and expansionary states of the economy that we studied
 in 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
ExpectedReturnChapter
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $K=2$
\end_inset

).
 The linear models we have discussed so far are ill suited to this task
 – we need to map their output (which we assume to be a scalar 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{y}$
\end_inset

) to exactly one these 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 categories, to which we assign the numeric values 
\begin_inset Formula $1,\,2,\,\cdots,\,K$
\end_inset

.
 This process, which is known as 
\emph on
classification
\emph default
, can be done in a number of ways, including:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If the categories are naturally ordered, we can use a regularized regression
 algorithm to regress their numerical values against the features, and map
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{y}$
\end_inset

 to a category by comparing it to a set of 
\begin_inset Formula $K-1$
\end_inset

 thresholds 
\begin_inset Formula $-\infty<\,T_{1}<\,T_{2}<\cdots<\,T_{K-1}<\infty$
\end_inset

, and output 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $C_{1}\ \mathrm{if}\ \hat{y}\ \leqslant\ T_{1}$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $C_{2}\ \mathrm{if}\ T_{1}\ <\ \hat{y}\ \leqslant\ T_{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\vdots$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $C_{K}\ \mathrm{if}\ T_{K-1}\ <\ \hat{y}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
If the categories are not naturally ordered, we can create a set of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 linear models, one for each class 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{j},\ 1\,\leqslant\,j\,\leqslant\,K$
\end_inset

, by associating the feature matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{X}$
\end_inset

 with a matching set of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 binary response vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}^{j},\ 1\,\leqslant\,j\,\leqslant\,K$
\end_inset

, whose 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{th}$
\end_inset

 row is 1 (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}_{i}^{j}=1$
\end_inset

) if the 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{th}$
\end_inset

 item belongs to 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{j}$
\end_inset

 and 0 otherwise.
 Given a new feature vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

, we input its values into all 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 models and assign the observation to 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{j}$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{y}_{j}$
\end_inset

, the fitted output of the 
\begin_inset Formula $j^{th}$
\end_inset

 model is the largest of the 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 fitted outputs.
 In essence, each one of the models makes a prediction about the class of
 the observation, which is then assigned to the class it most closely resembles.
 While attractive in theory, this method often fails in practice when 
\begin_inset Formula $K>2$
\end_inset

, as some classes get masked by other classes.
 The masking problem can be solved using 
\emph on
linear discriminant analysis
\emph default
, but the distributional assumptions required by it are restrictive, and
 we do not pursue it further.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If the identification problem maps naturally to one of choosing the class
 with the highest posterior probability, and if the sum of all the class
 probabilities is 1, we can apply a non-linear transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $g(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 to map 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{y}_{j}$
\end_inset

 to the probability that the given features correspond to an item from 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{j}$
\end_inset

, for 
\begin_inset Formula $1\,\leqslant\,j\,\leqslant\,K$
\end_inset

.
 This is most easily done using 
\emph on
logistic regression
\emph default
 when there are only two classes, which, for convenience, we label 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{2}$
\end_inset

, and to which we assign values of 0 and 1 respectively.
 This requires only a single linear model that relates 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{X}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

, the class response vector,
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}_{i}=0$
\end_inset

 if the 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{th}$
\end_inset

 row of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{X}$
\end_inset

 is associated with 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{1}$
\end_inset

 and is 1 if it is associated with 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and we simplify notation by using 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{y}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(\hat{y}\right)$
\end_inset

 to denote its output and its transformed output respectively.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the first case, both the model and the thresholds must be determined
 using cross-validation.
 Candidate models include the classical and robust regularized models described
 earlier in this chapter.
 In the second, multiple distributional assumptions, along with assumptions
 about the independence of measurements and the covariance of observations
 within classes must be made in order to operationalize it.
 As these assumptions are not true of most finance data sets, we do not
 pursue it further.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The third approach is widely used, and we focus on the 
\begin_inset Formula $K=2$
\end_inset

 case to build our intuition before outlining the mathematics of the general
 case.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Logistic Regression
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Logistic regression usefully bridges two observations:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The response of a linear model, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{y}$
\end_inset

, is unbounded on either side of the real line, and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Probability distributions are increasing and non-negative, and are bounded
 between 0 and 1.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These observations can be reconciled by mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{y}$
\end_inset

 to the conditional probability that an observation 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}=\left(x_{1},\ x_{2},\ \cdots,\ x_{p}\right)^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 is associated with 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{2}$
\end_inset

 via an appropriate 
\emph on
link function
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(\cdot\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Cumulative distribution functions are well suited to use as link functions
 as they naturally map the real line to 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,\ 1]$
\end_inset

, and we therefore write
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
While 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Probit"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 maps 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{y}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $p\left(\mathbf{x}\right)$
\end_inset

 via 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(\cdot\right)$
\end_inset

, it is equally common to see 
\begin_inset Formula $p\left(\mathbf{x}\right)$
\end_inset

 being mapped to 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{y}$
\end_inset

 via 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{-1}\left(\cdot\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
g\left(\hat{y}\right) & =F\left(\hat{y},\ \butheta\right),\ -\infty\,<\,\hat{y}\,<\,\infty,\nonumber \\
 & =Pr\left[\mathbf{x}\in C_{2}\right]\nonumber \\
 & \triangleq p\left(\mathbf{x}\right).\label{eq:Probit}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $F(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 takes as its inputs a vector of parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\butheta$
\end_inset

, as well as 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{y}=\mathbf{x}^{\prime}\,\bubeta$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 is a column vector of features associated with the observation and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bubeta$
\end_inset

 is the coefficient vector generated by the linear model.
 Finally, 
\begin_inset Formula $p\left(\mathbf{x}\right)$
\end_inset

 is the probability that this observation is associated with 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Correspondingly, 
\begin_inset Formula $1\,-\,p\left(\mathbf{x}\right)$
\end_inset

 is the probability that it is associated with 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The model must be estimated by optimizing over 
\begin_inset Formula $F(\cdot),\ \butheta$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bubeta$
\end_inset

 using maximum likelihood estimation and/or cross-validation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Allowing complete freedom in the choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $F(\cdot)$
\end_inset

 so underconstrains the problem that no unique solution can be found.
 In practice, therefore, we restrict the allowable family of distributions.
 The two most widely used families are the Normal (in which case the model
 is known as a 
\emph on
probit
\emph default
 model) or the 
\emph on
logit
\emph default
 (in which case it is known as logistic regression), and it is the second
 that has come to dominate usage, largely on account of its lower computational
 complexity.
 With appropriate scaling, the normal and logit densities almost overlap
 each other, so the results derived from their use are almost identical.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Logistic regression starts by mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $p\left(\mathbf{x}\right)$
\end_inset

 to the entire real line using the logit, or the quantile function of the
 standard logistic distribution:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\hat{y} & =\mathbf{x}^{\prime}\,\bubeta\nonumber \\
 & =\ln\left(\frac{p\left(\mathbf{x}\right)}{1\,-\,p\left(\mathbf{x}\right)}\right).\label{eq:LogisticTransform}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The bracketed term on the right hand side of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:LogisticTransform"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is known as the 
\emph on
odds
\emph default
 (the entire right hand side is known as the 
\emph on
log odds
\emph default
) and can take any positive value.
 It is easily seen that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
p\left(\mathbf{x}\right)=\frac{\mathrm{odds}}{1\,+\,\mathrm{odds}},\label{eq:OddsVsP}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:LogisticTransform"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is easily inverted to give 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
p\left(\mathbf{x}\right) & =g\left(\hat{y}\right)\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{\exp\left(\hat{y}\right)}{1\,+\,\exp\left(\hat{y}\right)}\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{\exp\left(\mathbf{x}^{\prime}\,\bubeta\right)}{1\,+\,\exp\left(\mathbf{x}^{\prime}\,\bubeta\right)}\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{1}{1\,+\,\exp\left(-\mathbf{x}^{\prime}\,\bubeta\right)}.\label{eq:LogisticTransform2}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When we are given a feature matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{X}$
\end_inset

 whose 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{th}$
\end_inset

 row is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{X}_{i}$
\end_inset

, we correspondingly write
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
p\left(\mathbf{X}_{i}\right) & =g\left(\hat{y}_{i}\right)\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{\exp\left(\hat{y}_{i}\right)}{1\,+\,\exp\left(\hat{y}_{i}\right)}\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{\exp\left(\mathbf{X}_{i}\,\bubeta\right)}{1\,+\,\exp\left(\mathbf{X}_{i}\,\bubeta\right)}\nonumber \\
 & =\frac{1}{1\,+\,\exp\left(-\mathbf{X}_{i}\,\bubeta\right)}.\label{eq:LogisticTransform3}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the rows of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{X}$
\end_inset

 are independent, we can use the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}_{i}$
\end_inset

 is binary to write the log-likelihood function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\bubeta$
\end_inset

 as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
l(\bubeta) & =\ln\ L(\bubeta)\nonumber \\
 & =\ln\left(\prod_{i\,=\,1}^{N}\left(p\left(\mathbf{X}_{i}\right)\right)^{\mathbf{c}_{i}}\left(1\,-\,p\left(\mathbf{X}_{i}\right)\right)^{1-\mathbf{c}_{i}}\right)\nonumber \\
 & =\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{N}\mathbf{c}_{i}\cdot\ln\,p\left(\mathbf{X}_{i}\right)\ +\ \left(1\,-\,\mathbf{c}_{i}\right)\cdot\ln\,\left(1\,-\,p\left(\mathbf{X}_{i}\right)\right)\nonumber \\
 & =\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{N}\mathbf{c}_{i}\cdot\ln\,\left(\frac{p\left(\mathbf{X}_{i}\right)}{1\,-\,p\left(\mathbf{X}_{i}\right)}\right)\ +\ \sum_{i\,=\,1}^{N}\cdot\ln\,\left(1\,-\,p\left(\mathbf{X}_{i}\right)\right)\nonumber \\
 & =\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{N}\mathbf{c}_{i}\cdot\mathbf{X}_{i}\,\bubeta\ -\ \sum_{i\,=\,1}^{N}\ln\left(1\,+\,\exp\left(\mathbf{X}_{i}\,\bubeta\right)\right).\label{eq:LogLikelihoodLogisticRegression}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is easily shown that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\nabla l(\bubeta) & =\frac{\partial l(\bubeta)}{\partial\bubeta}\nonumber \\
 & =\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{N}\left(\mathbf{c}_{i}\,-\,\frac{\exp\left(\mathbf{X}_{i}\,\bubeta\right)}{1+\exp\left(\mathbf{X}_{i}\,\bubeta\right)}\right)\mathbf{X}_{i}^{\prime}\label{eq:LogisticRegressionGradient}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathbf{H}(\bubeta) & =\frac{\partial^{2}l(\bubeta)}{\partial\bubeta\partial\bubeta^{\prime}}\nonumber \\
 & =-\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{N}\mathbf{X}_{i}^{\prime}\,\mathbf{X}_{i}\,\frac{\exp\left(\mathbf{X}_{i}\,\bubeta\right)}{\left(1+\exp\left(\mathbf{X}_{i}\,\bubeta\right)\right)^{2}}.\label{eq:LogisticRegressionHessian}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We identify 
\begin_inset Formula $\bubeta_{Logistic\ Regression}$
\end_inset

 by setting
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\nabla l(\bubeta)=\mathbf{0},\label{eq:LogisticRegressionEstimatingEquation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

and then using gradient descent to iteratively identify the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\bubeta$
\end_inset

 that solves 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:LogisticRegressionEstimatingEquation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 The relevant details can be found in Section 4.4.1 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "HastieTibshiraniFriedman2009"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Logistic regression, like the other linear models we earlier described,
 can be regularized, and 
\family typewriter
glmnet
\family default
 allows the addition of an elastic net penalty to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:LogLikelihoodLogisticRegression"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 The corresponding loss function is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathscr{L}_{LR}\left(\mathbf{X},\ \mathbf{y},\ \mu,\ \bubeta\right)=-\frac{1}{N}\,l(\bubeta)\,+\,\lambda_{LR}\left(\alpha\left\Vert \bubeta\right\Vert _{1}\,+\,\frac{\left(1-\alpha\right)}{2}\left\Vert \bubeta\right\Vert _{2}\right),\ \ \lambda_{LR}\geqslant0,\ 0\leqslant\alpha\leqslant1
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Negating 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:LogLikelihoodLogisticRegression"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and dividing it by 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 turns the log-likelihood into an expected loss, and the addition of the
 elastic net penalty allows for variable selection and shrinkage.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{LR}=0$
\end_inset

, the loss function corresponds to classical logistic regression.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{LR}$
\end_inset

 increases, the choice of alpha determines whether the regularization is
 ridge-like, lasso-like or elastic net-like.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It proves useful to routinely include a small ridge penalty when running
 logistic regression to protect against divergence in the special case when
 the classes are completely separated and have no overlap.
 In this case, the MLE of 
\begin_inset Formula $\bubeta$
\end_inset

 is not unique, and some of its entries will become infinite.
 A small ridge penalty protects against this.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Robust logistic regression is subtly different from robust linear regression,
 as the respones fall into a finite number of buckets, so that while errors
 may exist in some responses, no outliers can exist.
 The features, on the other hand, are unbounded, and can act as 
\emph on
leverage points
\emph default
 if they lie far away from the majority of the features.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The influence function of 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:LogisticRegressionEstimatingEquation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, the MLE for Logistic Regression, can be shown to be (see Section 7.1 of
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Maronna2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Jann2020"
literal "false"

\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
IF\left(\mathbf{c},\ \mathbf{X},\ \bubeta\right)=\left(\frac{1}{N}\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{N}\mathbf{X}_{i}^{\prime}\,\mathbf{X}_{i}\,\frac{\exp\left(\mathbf{X}_{i}\,\bubeta\right)}{\left(1\,+\,\exp\left(\mathbf{X}_{i}\,\bubeta\right)\right)^{2}}\right)^{-1}\cdot\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{N}\left(\mathbf{c}_{i}\,-\,\frac{\exp\left(\mathbf{X}_{i}\,\bubeta\right)}{1\,+\,\exp\left(\mathbf{X}_{i}\,\bubeta\right)}\right)\mathbf{X}_{i}^{\prime}.\label{eq:LogisticRegressionIF}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

As the first term 
\begin_inset Formula $\longrightarrow\left(E\left(\mathbf{x^{\prime}}\,\mathbf{x}\,\frac{\exp\left(\mathbf{x}\,\bubeta\right)}{\left(1\,+\,\exp\left(\mathbf{x}\,\bubeta\right)\right)^{2}}\right)\right)^{-1}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 represents a random row of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{X}$
\end_inset

, and as the magnitude of bracketed term in the sum is bounded by 1, the
 primary determinant of the impact of an added observation on 
\begin_inset Formula $\bubeta$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{X}_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Robust logistic regression applies a data-dependent weight 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{W}_{i}$
\end_inset

 that depends on how far 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{X}_{i}$
\end_inset

 is from its distribution to the estimating equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:LogisticRegressionEstimatingEquation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, which now becomes 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{i\,=\,1}^{N}\mathbf{W}_{i}\left(\mathbf{c}_{i}\,-\,\frac{\exp\left(\mathbf{X}_{i}\,\bubeta\right)}{1\,+\,\exp\left(\mathbf{X}_{i}\,\bubeta\right)}\right)\mathbf{X}_{i}^{\prime}=\mathbf{0},\label{eq:RobustLogisticRegressionMLE}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where the vector of weights 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{W}$
\end_inset

 is derived from a robust estimate of the Mahalonobis distances of the rows
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{X}$
\end_inset

 from their common distribution.
 Points that lie further away from the distribution are downweighted so
 as not to distort the estimate of 
\begin_inset Formula $\bubeta$
\end_inset

.
 The details are complex and can be found in Section 7.2 of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Maronna2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The R package 
\family typewriter
RobstatTM
\family default
 implements the weighted robust logistic regression algorithm 
\family typewriter
logregWBY
\family default
 that was first described in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "BiancoYohai1996"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and further enhanced in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "CrouxHaesbroeck2003"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Projection Pursuit Regression and Neural Networks
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Projection Pursuit 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Least squares and its derivatives provide powerful ways by which to identify
 structure in a high-dimensional space by optimally projecting features
 onto a low-dimensional subspace, most often a hyperplane.
 But what if the features can be made more visually informative by first
 scaling and rotating, and perhaps even discarding, some of their components
 before projecting them? Or if they exhibit clustering when projected onto
 some special hyperplane? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Projections"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 illustrates the nature of the problem.
 The data plotted is a mixture of two independent random variables 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{1}$
\end_inset

 is normally distributed with mean 1.5 and variance 1, while 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{2}$
\end_inset

 is exponential with mean 1.
 The plotted variables 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 are derived from 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{2}$
\end_inset

 as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
X & =Z_{1}\ \mathrm{w.p.}\ \frac{2}{3},\ 1-Z_{2}\ \mathrm{w.p}.\ \frac{1}{3}\\
Y & =Z_{1}\ \mathrm{w.p.}\ \frac{2}{3},\ \phantom{1-Z_{2}}-Z_{2}\ \mathrm{w.p}.\ \frac{1}{3}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The scatter plot at the top left displays the actual data, while the density
 plot at the top right clearly shows the concentration of the points.
 The separation between the two distributions is clear, and a 
\begin_inset Formula $45^{\circ}$
\end_inset

 line nicely separates the two distributions.
 The density of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 (bottom left), however, shows only a single peak, and that of 
\begin_inset Formula $Y$
\end_inset

 (bottom right), identifies both peaks, but suggests that the two distributions
 are almost equally likely.
\end_layout

