\begin_layout Standard
Projection pursuit
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The catchy name appears to have been first mentioned in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "FriedmanTukey1974"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is the process of exposing structure in a feature matrix beyond its covariance
 matrix by maximizing an appropriately chosen 
\emph on
projection index 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

.

\emph default
 The value of the projection index ought to reflect how interesting a particular
 projection of the features might be to an analyst.
 The notion of interestingness is application dependent, but is often interprete
d as how non-normal the distribution of the projected data is.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One-dimensional projection pursuit searches for a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\bubeta_{1}$
\end_inset

 that best exposes the underlying structure of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{X}$
\end_inset

 by maximizing 
\begin_inset Formula $I\left(\mathbf{X}^{\prime}\,\bubeta\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Two-dimensional projection pursuit adds a second projection vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\bubeta_{2}$
\end_inset

 as well as a bivariate projection index 
\begin_inset Formula $I\left(\mathbf{X}^{\prime}\,\bubeta_{1},\ \mathbf{X}^{\prime}\,\bubeta_{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 that is maximized when interesting structure in the joint density of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{X}$
\end_inset

 in two orthogonal directions is best exposed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Projection pursuit is often used to maximally separate clusters in a feature
 matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{X}$
\end_inset

, and so lends itself to both supervised and unsupervised learning.
 Projection pursuit regression goes a step further – it applies nonlinear
 transformations to projections of data on a collection of identified proejction
 vectors to obtain a better regression surface.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The R packages 
\family typewriter
Pursuit, tourr
\family default
 and 
\family typewriter
REPPlab
\family default
 allow one to explore and visualize various projections of a data set, and
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Iris1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 displays two projections of the famous 
\family typewriter
iris
\family default
 dataset along two axes using 
\family typewriter
Pursuit::GrandTour
\family default
.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
See 
\begin_inset Flex URL
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iris_flower_data_set
\end_layout

\end_inset

 for the history of this dataset, which is widely used in machine learning.
 It contains 4 measurements (the length and the width of petals and sepals)
 on 150 flowers representing three species of irises.
 The measurements were made by Edgar Anderson and the data set was made
 famous by Sir Ronald Fisher in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Fisher1936"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The plot on the left displays the raw data projected without any attempt
 to maximize separation between classes, and evidences significant overlap
 between the three species.
 The plot on the right, in contrast, shows how an optimal projection allows
 error-free identification of all irises of species setosa, and excellent,
 though not perfect, separation of the two other species (versicolor and
 virginica.)
\end_layout

