\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Kruskal1969"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 initiated work on projection pursuit by searching for clusters that maximize
 an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

index of condensation
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 which he defined to be the coefficient of variation of the inter-point
 distances generated by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{X}\bubeta$
\end_inset

, i.e.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
I_{Kruskal}=\frac{\sigma_{y_{i}-y_{j}}}{\overline{y_{i}-y_{j}}}.\label{eq:KruskalCondensation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The intuition that motivates 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:KruskalCondensation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is simple: if projecting 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{X}$
\end_inset

 onto 
\begin_inset Formula $\bubeta$
\end_inset

 results in a few well-separated clusters of points, the average inter-point
 distance within clusters will be small, while the average inter-point distance
 across clusters will be large, simultaneously increasing its numerator
 and decreasing its denominator.
 Unfortunately 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{Kruskal}$
\end_inset

 is not robust to outliers, though it can be improved using robust estimates
 of both the numerator and denominator.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Over the years, many such indices have been identified, and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "HouWentzell2011"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 use kurtosis as an index to identify the directions 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}_{i}$
\end_inset

 that maximize cluster separation by 
\emph on
minimizing
\emph default
 the kurtosis of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}_{i}\cdot\mathbf{y}$
\end_inset

.
 Their technique rests on 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Moors1986"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 observation that kurtosis measures the dispersion of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 around both 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu-\sigma$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu+\sigma$
\end_inset

, making its minimization a simple way by which to optimally separate observatio
ns into two classes, one centered at 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu-\sigma$
\end_inset

 and the other at 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu+\sigma$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\kappa & =E\left[\left(\frac{x\ -\ \mu}{\sigma}\right)^{4}\right]\nonumber \\
 & =E\left[\left(\left(\frac{x\ -\ \mu}{\sigma}\right)^{2}\right)^{2}\right]\nonumber \\
 & =E\left[\left(\left(\frac{x\ -\ \mu}{\sigma}\right)^{2}\right)\right]^{2}\ +\ \mathrm{var}\left(\left(\frac{x\ -\ \mu}{\sigma}\right)^{2}\right)\nonumber \\
 & =1\ +\ \mathrm{var}\left(\left(\frac{x\ -\ \mu}{\sigma}\right)^{2}\right)\label{eq:KurtosisForICA}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

