\begin_layout Standard
Projection pursuit analysis (PPA) has much in common with Independent Components
 Analysis (ICA), which in turn is related to Principal Components Analysis
 (PCA).
 The links between the techniques are addressed briefly in Chapter 14 of
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "HastieTibshiraniFriedman2009"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and are developed comprehensively in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "HyvarinenOja2000"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "HyvarinenKaarhunenOja2001"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Projection Pursuit Regression
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "FriedmanStuetzle1981"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 use the projections identified by PPA to usefully generalize Least Squares
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
See 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
ProbabilityAppendix
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset

for a development of Least Squares.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 by writing 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{y}=\overline{y}\ +\ \sum_{i=1}^{m}f_{i}\left(\mathbf{x}^{\prime}\,\bubeta_{i}\right),\label{eq:PPR1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\bubeta_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{th}$
\end_inset

 projection,
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
These may not be identical to the projections identified by projection pursuit.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i},\ 1\leqslant i\leqslant m$
\end_inset

 are smooth 
\emph on
ridge functions
\emph default
, or functions that vary only in the direction of 
\begin_inset Formula $\bubeta$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
See 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "KonyaginKuleshovMaiorov2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 for the theory of ridge functions.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The ridge functions in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:PPR1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

are not restricted to be linear, allowing it to capture nonlinearities in
 the relationship between 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 Most importantly, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "DiaconisShahshahani1984"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 show that ridge functions possess a universal approximation property –
 any function of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 variables can be appproximated arbitrarily well by ridge functions for
 sufficiently large 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

, echoing the Stone-Weierstrass Theorem for continuous functions on Hausdorff
 spaces.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "FriedmanStuetzle1981"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 call their method Projection Pursuit Regression (PPR) and present an iterative
 algorithm for identifying 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bubeta_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Even though the algorithm is refined in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Friedman1985"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Friedman1987"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, we present only the original version, both for ease of exposition and
 for relevance.
 In spite of its distinguished parentage, PPR is no longer widely used,
 and lives on primarily as the intellectual predecessor of neural networks,
 largely on account of the universal approximation property they share.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float algorithm
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Enumerate

\family typewriter
Initialize:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $i\longleftarrow1$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $m\longleftarrow m_{max}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\family typewriter
Demean the response vector
\family default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{y}_{1}\longleftarrow\mathbf{y}-\bar{\mathbf{y}}\mathbf{1}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace defskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate

\family typewriter
While 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\ 2,\cdots,\ m$
\end_inset

 and (
\begin_inset Formula $res^{2}$
\end_inset

> Threshold):
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate

\family typewriter
Compute the residuals 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{\bueps}_{i}\longleftarrow\mathbf{y}_{i}\ -\ \sum_{j=1}^{i-1}f_{j}\left(\mathbf{X}\,\bubeta_{j}\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\family typewriter
Search for and dentify the 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{th}$
\end_inset

 projection vector 
\family default

\begin_inset Formula $\bubeta_{i}$
\end_inset

 
\family typewriter
and ridge function
\family default
 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}$
\end_inset

 
\family typewriter
that minimizes the sum of squared residuals
\family default
 
\begin_inset Formula $res^{2}=\left(\mathrm{\bueps}_{i}\ -\ f_{i}\left(\mathbf{X}\,\bubeta_{i}\right)\right)^{\prime}\left(\mathrm{\bueps}_{i}\ -\ f_{i}\left(\mathbf{X}\,\bubeta_{i}\right)\right)$
\end_inset

 , where 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i}\left(\cdot\right)$
\end_inset

is applied to each component of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{X}\,\bubeta_{i}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "alg:FriedmanSteutzlePPR"

\end_inset

The Friedman-Steutzle algorithm for Projection Pursuit Regression
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Algorithm 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "alg:FriedmanSteutzlePPR"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is a forward stagewise procedure – once a projection vector is identified,
 it is not modified in later stages.
 In contrast, the SMART algorithm decribed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Friedman1985"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 directly minimizes the sum of squared residuals by iteratively minimizing
 the magnitude of the residual 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:PPR1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 using a Gauss-Newton iteration
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
m^{*},\ \mathbf{f}^{*},\ \bubeta^{*}=\underset{m,\ f_{i},\ \bubeta_{i}}{argmin}\left(\mathbf{y}\ -\ \bar{\mathbf{y}}\mathbf{1}\ -\ \sum_{i=1}^{m}f_{i}\left(\mathbf{X}\,\bubeta_{i}\right)\right)^{\prime}\left(\mathbf{y}\ -\ \bar{\mathbf{y}}\mathbf{1}\ -\ \sum_{i=1}^{m}f_{i}\left(\mathbf{X}\,\bubeta_{i}\right)\right),\label{eq:SMARTppr}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $m^{*},\ \mathbf{f}^{*}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bubeta^{*}$
\end_inset

 are the optimal values of 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{i},\ 1\leqslant i\leqslant m$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bubeta_{i},\ 1\leqslant i\leqslant m$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The two solutions can be strikingly different, particularly when the features
 are almost collinear.
 The SMART algorithm is available as the Base R functions 
\family typewriter
ppr
\family default
 and 
\family typewriter
plot.ppr
\family default
.
 
\end_layout

